{"title_page": "R (March) v Secretary of State for Health", "text_new": "{{coi|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|UK judicial review quashing a decision on the grounds of material error of fact}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n| name = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health\n| image = \n| court = High Court\n| date decided = 16 April 2010\n| full name = The Queen (on the application of Andrew Michael March) v The Secretary of State for Health\n| citations = [2010] [https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html EWHC 765 (Admin)]\n| judges = [[James Holman (judge)|Mr Justice Holman]]\n| prior actions =  \n| subsequent actions = \n| opinions = \n| transcripts =\n| keywords = Material error of fact; Relevance of Hansard\n}}\n\n'''''R (March) v Secretary of State for Health''''' was a successful 2010 [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] which challenged the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health's]] decision not to implement Recommendation 6(h) of the Archer Independent Inquiry.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57}}</ref> \nThe case was important in developing the doctrine of ''error of fact'' in [[public law]] which previously had not readily been the subject of judicial intervention.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=2008 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Fifth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=468 |isbn=9781841138244 |quote= ''Judicial review judges have traditionally been cautious about fact-based challenges''.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Demetriou |first1=Marie |last2= Houseman |first2= Stephen |date= 1997|title=Review for Error of Fact\u2014A Brief Guide |url= https://doi.org/10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 |journal=JR |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |doi= 10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 | publisher = Routledge |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = ''E'' v. Secretary of State for the Home Department |link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html |court = EWCA | division = Civ |year = 2004 |num = 49 |parallelcite = [2004] QB 1044 |para=51}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\n\n[[Andrew March|Andrew Michael March]], a [[haemophilia|haemophiliac]],<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |last1= Meikle |first1= James  |date= 2010-04-16 |title= Court ruling may help contaminated blood victims win higher payouts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote= ''A classical music composer who was infected by HIV when he was nine, who later developed hepatitis, won a judicial review that challenged the basis of health ministers' decision last year not to increase the payments.''}}</ref> along with several thousand other patients was treated with contaminated blood products in the 1970\u2032s and 1980\u2032s.<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |date= 2010-04-16 |title=Composer wins compensation review over contaminated blood |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote=An award-winning composer who contracted HIV and Hepatitis C through NHS treatment with contaminated blood products has won a legal challenge over compensation payments.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood and blood products]] disaster also occurred in the [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /> and various compensation schemes and statutory provisions were put in place between 1991 and 2002 on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the state.<ref>{{cite letter| first = Lara| last = Hynes| recipient = Mark A. Ward| subject = RE: Blood & Tissue Policy Division, (DOHC)| language = English| date = {{date|2009-07-30|mdy}}| quote =''The scheme of compensation for persons with haemophilia was put in place on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the State''}}</ref> However, the level of payments made to similarly infected and affected people in the Republic of Ireland was considerably greater than payments made to victims in the United Kingdom. In the UK, the Department of Health had consistently refused to increase the ''[[ex gratia]]'' support payments to be on a par with the more generous levels of payments made in the Republic of Ireland, arguing that [[Legal liability|liability]] in the UK had never been established, whilst in Ireland there had been findings of fault.<ref name=\"Guardian1\" /><ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Topical Questions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2009-06-23/debates/b27195ce-b353-48b1-b120-8b64dbd4470d/CommonsChamber |date=June 23, 2009 |volume=494 |column=656 |speaker= Gillian Merron |position= Minister of State at the Department of Health}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [27] [30] [34]}}</ref> This was found to be incorrect since the basis behind the Irish scheme was compassion, not fault.\n\nThe ministerial decision at the centre of this judicial review hinged on the refusal to adopt a key recommendation of the independent, non-statutory Archer Inquiry. In particular, the Minister rejected Recommendation 6(h), which read as follows: ''\u2033We suggest that payments should be at least the equivalent of those payable under the scheme which applies at any time in Ireland.\u2033''<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Archer Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=12 |page=107-110 |access-date=2010-04-11 |quote=''We believe that the following recommendations would help to meet the unmet needs of patients with haemophilia and their families...''}}</ref>\n\n==Judgment==\n\nThe judgement was handed down by Mr Justice Holman on Friday, 16th April 2010. {{quote box |width=30%|style=min-width:12em|''The thrust of the case on behalf of the claimant is that the answers given by the minister on 23 June and 1 July, when considered separately or cumulatively, reveal a material error of fact on the part of the government as to the situation in Ireland; that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h); and, accordingly, that the government should be required to reconsider their response to recommendation 6 (h)''.|source=\u2014 Mr Justice Holman<ref name=\"Bailii1\"/>}}\n\n===Material error of fact===\nThe ''March'' case demonstrates that the jurisdiction of the court extends to quashing a decision if the published reasons for the decision contain an error which is considered capable of making a material difference to the outcome of the decision had the error in question not been made.<ref>{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |date= June 2011 |title= Administrative Law |edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ |location=Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |page=333 |chapter=9.2.3 |isbn=9780199601752 |quote=''An error of fact revolution?''}}</ref>  The essence of the error was that the Irish government decided to make payments at a substantial level, very much like compensation, but strictly speaking were ''ex gratia'' in nature and they decided to do this before there was any finding of fault.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Fordham|first=Michael|title=Judicial Review Handbook|publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |date=2012|edition=6th|isbn=9781849461597}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clements|first=Richard|title=Public Law\u2014Blackstone\u2032s questions & answers|publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2015|edition=Eighth|isbn=9780198715733}}\n*{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |title= Administrative Law |date= 2011|edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA333&ots=fISK8plf4X&dq=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&f=false |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199601752}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Abrogation in Public Law]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "text_old": "{{coi|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|UK judicial review quashing a decision on the grounds of material error of fact}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n| name = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health\n| image = \n| court = High Court\n| date decided = 16 April 2010\n| full name = The Queen (on the application of Andrew Michael March) v The Secretary of State for Health\n| citations = [2010] [https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html EWHC 765 (Admin)]\n| judges = [[James Holman (judge)|Mr Justice Holman]]\n| prior actions =  \n| subsequent actions = \n| opinions = \n| transcripts =\n| keywords = Material error of fact; Relevance of Hansard\n}}\n\n'''''R (March) v Secretary of State for Health''''' was a successful 2010 [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] which challenged the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health's]] decision not to implement Recommendation 6(h) of the Archer Independent Inquiry.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57}}</ref> \nThe case was important in developing the doctrine of ''error of fact'' in [[public law]] which previously had not readily been the subject of judicial intervention.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=2008 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Fifth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=468 |isbn=9781841138244 |quote= ''Judicial review judges have traditionally been cautious about fact-based challenges''.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Demetriou |first1=Marie |last2= Houseman |first2= Stephen |date= 1997|title=Review for Error of Fact\u2014A Brief Guide |url= https://doi.org/10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 |journal=JR |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |doi= 10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 | publisher = Routledge |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = ''E'' v. Secretary of State for the Home Department |link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html |court = EWCA | division = Civ |year = 2004 |num = 49 |parallelcite = [2004] QB 1044 |para=51}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\n\n[[Andrew March|Andrew Michael March]], a [[haemophilia|haemophiliac]],<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |last1= Meikle |first1= James  |date= 2010-04-16 |title= Court ruling may help contaminated blood victims win higher payouts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote= ''A classical music composer who was infected by HIV when he was nine, who later developed hepatitis, won a judicial review that challenged the basis of health ministers' decision last year not to increase the payments.''}}</ref> along with several thousand other patients was treated with contaminated blood products in the 1970\u2032s and 1980\u2032s.<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |date= 2010-04-16 |title=Composer wins compensation review over contaminated blood |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote=An award-winning composer who contracted HIV and Hepatitis C through NHS treatment with contaminated blood products has won a legal challenge over compensation payments.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood and blood products]] disaster also occurred in the [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /> and various compensation schemes and statutory provisions were put in place between 1991 and 2002 on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the state.<ref>{{cite letter| first = Lara| last = Hynes| recipient = Mark A. Ward| subject = RE: Blood & Tissue Policy Division, (DOHC)| language = English| date = {{date|2009-07-30|mdy}}| quote =''The scheme of compensation for persons with haemophilia was put in place on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the State''}}</ref> However, the level of payments made to similarly infected and affected people in the Republic of Ireland was considerably greater than payments made to victims in the United Kingdom. In the UK, the Department of Health had consistently refused to increase the ''[[ex gratia]]'' support payments to be on a par with the more generous levels of payments made in the Republic of Ireland, arguing that [[Legal liability|liability]] in the UK had never been established, whilst in Ireland there had been findings of fault.<ref name=\"Guardian1\" /><ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Topical Questions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2009-06-23/debates/b27195ce-b353-48b1-b120-8b64dbd4470d/CommonsChamber |date=June 23, 2009 |volume=494 |column=656 |speaker= Gillian Merron |position= Minister of State at the Department of Health}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [27] [30] [34]}}</ref> This was found to be incorrect since the basis behind the Irish scheme was compassion, not fault.\n\nThe ministerial decision at the centre of this judicial review hinged on the refusal to adopt a key recommendation of the independent, non-statutory Archer Inquiry. In particular, the Minister rejected Recommendation 6(h), which read as follows: ''\u2033We suggest that payments should be at least the equivalent of those payable under the scheme which applies at any time in Ireland.\u2033''<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Archer Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=12 |page=107-110 |access-date=2010-04-11 |quote=''We believe that the following recommendations would help to meet the unmet needs of patients with haemophilia and their families...''}}</ref>\n\n==Judgment==\n\nThe judgement was handed down by Mr Justice Holman on Friday, 16th April 2010. {{quote box |width=30%|style=min-width:12em|''The thrust of the case on behalf of the claimant is that the answers given by the minister on 23 June and 1 July, when considered separately or cumulatively, reveal a material error of fact on the part of the government as to the situation in Ireland; that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h); and, accordingly, that the government should be required to reconsider their response to recommendation 6 (h)''.|source=\u2014 Mr Justice Holman<ref name=\"Bailii1\"/>}}\n\n===Material error of fact===\nThe ''March'' case demonstrates that the jurisdiction of the court extends to quashing a decision if the published reasons for the decision contain an error which is considered capable of making a material difference to the outcome of the decision had the error in question not been made.<ref>{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |date= June 2011 |title= Administrative Law |edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ |location=Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |page=333 |chapter=9.2.3 |isbn=9780199601752 |quote=''An error of fact revolution?''}}</ref>  The essence of the error was that the Irish government decided to make payments at a substantial level, very much like compensation, but strictly speaking ''ex gratia'' in nature, before there was any finding of fault.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Fordham|first=Michael|title=Judicial Review Handbook|publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |date=2012|edition=6th|isbn=9781849461597}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clements|first=Richard|title=Public Law\u2014Blackstone\u2032s questions & answers|publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2015|edition=Eighth|isbn=9780198715733}}\n*{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |title= Administrative Law |date= 2011|edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA333&ots=fISK8plf4X&dq=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&f=false |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199601752}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Abrogation in Public Law]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "